The paper proposes a new graph pooling operation for deep graph neural networks (GNNs) and demonstrates its effectiveness in graph classification tasks. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) or computer vision (cs.CV) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper uses compressive Haar transforms, which are commonly used in signal processing and image analysis, indicating a potential fit for the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also discusses the preservation of structure information in the input graph, which aligns with the neural networks and deep learning (cs.NE) sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes a new technique for graph pooling, which could be relevant to the social and information networks (cs.SI) sub-category.
